alse,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for interpretation of a screening test result. You review a recent study evaluating a new screening test for breast cancer. The study included 1,500 patients. Of the 100 patients with cancer, 75 tested positive and 25 tested negative. Of the 1,400 patients without cancer, 180 tested positive and 1,220 tested negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the negative predictive value of this screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["80%","87%","98%","92%","85%"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of diagnostic test characteristics. The key components can be organised in a two-by-two table:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctbody\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECancer Present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECancer Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETest Positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003E75\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003E180\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETest Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1220\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/tbody\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E98%\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct negative predictive value (NPV). NPV is calculated as TN/(TN+FN). From the table, TN=1220 and FN=25, so NPV = 1220/(1220+25) = 1220/1245 = 98%. This means that when this test is negative, there is a 98% probability that the person truly does not have cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E80%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the sensitivity, calculated as TP/(TP+FN) = 75/(75+25) = 75/100 = 75%. This is the proportion of people with cancer who test positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E87%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the specificity, calculated as TN/(TN+FP) = 1220/(1220+180) = 1220/1400 = 87%. This is the proportion of people without cancer who test negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these test characteristics is crucial for interpreting diagnostic tests in clinical practice. NPV is particularly important when ruling out serious conditions, as it tells us how confident we can be that a negative test truly indicates absence of disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Negative predictive value is calculated by true negatives/(true negatives + false negatives).","Negative predictive value is the probability that a person who tested negative truly does not have the condition.","Two-by-two tables are useful tools for calculating diagnostic test characteristics."],"references":["Trevethan R. Sensitivity, Specificity, and Predictive Values: Foundations, Pliabilities, and Pitfalls in Research and Practice. Front Public Health. 2017;5:307. Published 2017 Nov 20. doi:10.3389/fpubh.2017.00307"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanation